1. Define the interface first.

Create protocol-facing files such as:

kernel/ethernet.h
kernel/arp.h
kernel/ipv4.h
kernel/icmp.h
kernel/ipv4_icmp.cc or kernel/net_proto.cc

Add a small public entry point such as:

void net_handle_frame(const uint8_t* data, size_t len);
bool net_send_arp_reply(...);
bool net_send_icmp_echo_reply(...);

Depend only on Person 2’s raw API:

net_send_raw(...)
net_recv_raw(...)

Keep your layer independent of descriptors, rings, PCI, and MMIO. Your report already defines Person 3 as the protocol/ping layer on top of raw frames.

2. Define the core packet structures.

Add minimal packed structs for:

Ethernet header
ARP packet
IPv4 header
ICMP echo header

Add constants for:

EtherType values
ARP opcodes
IPv4 protocol values
ICMP echo request/reply types
header sizes
MTU or max frame assumptions if needed

Only include the fields needed for the ping demo. Do not design a full general-purpose stack.

3. Build the parsing/dispatch layer.

Implement a central parser:

check frame length
parse Ethernet header
dispatch by EtherType
reject unsupported or malformed frames safely

Then split into handlers such as:

handle_arp(...)
handle_ipv4(...)
handle_icmp(...)

Add safety checks for:

truncated frames
unsupported EtherTypes
bad IPv4 header length
bad protocol values
4. Build a fake/demo path so you can work before full integration.

Add a fake or direct test path where:

raw test frames can be passed into net_handle_frame(...)
ARP request bytes can be injected manually
ICMP echo request bytes can be injected manually
generated replies can be dumped or inspected without real hardware

This lets you validate protocol logic even if Person 1 and Person 2 are still finishing bring-up.

5. Implement ARP first.

Implement the minimum ARP support needed for ping:

parse incoming ARP requests
check whether the target IP matches your OS IP
construct a valid ARP reply
send the reply through net_send_raw(...)

Also decide:

whether to ignore unsupported ARP cases
whether you need a tiny ARP table or only immediate request/reply support

Keep it minimal.

6. Implement IPv4 + ICMP ping logic.

Implement the minimum needed for echo handling:

parse IPv4 header
verify destination IP
verify protocol is ICMP
parse ICMP echo request
construct ICMP echo reply
swap source/destination addresses
recompute checksums
send through net_send_raw(...)

Preserve the important request fields correctly:

ICMP identifier
sequence number
payload
7. Agree on the contract with Person 2.

Person 2 should provide only the raw packet API:

net_send_raw(...)
net_recv_raw(...) or equivalent receive hook
net_ready()

You should not know anything about:

virtqueues
descriptors
queue indices
MMIO registers
PCI enumeration

Decide early:

what net_recv_raw(...) returns when no packet is available
who owns the receive loop
whether your code is polling-based or callback-based
8. Agree on the contract with Person 1.

Person 1 should expose only minimal device/config information needed by your layer, such as:

local MAC address
whether NIC/network stack is ready
possibly the configured guest IP for the demo

Do not depend on bring-up details. Your code should only need final network identity values, not hardware initialization steps.

9. Add debug output early.

Log protocol-level events such as:

received EtherType
ARP request/reply seen
IPv4 packet received
ICMP echo request received
ICMP echo reply sent
dropped malformed frame
packet lengths
optional header dumps

Keep logs easy to disable so demo output stays clean.

10. Test without the real NIC.

Test these cases first:

inject fake ARP request, confirm ARP reply is produced
inject fake ICMP echo request, confirm echo reply is produced
verify malformed/truncated frames are rejected safely
verify wrong destination IP is ignored
verify checksums are computed correctly
verify payload survives request → reply path

This should work before full hardware integration.

11. Integration pass after Person 1 and Person 2 land.

Once the lower layers are ready:

connect your parser to the real receive path
use the real MAC/IP configuration
confirm ARP resolution happens in the live environment
confirm ICMP echo request is parsed correctly from real incoming frames
confirm echo reply reaches the sender
verify the final ping demo end-to-end